World leaders expressed condolences at the death of Japan's 87-year-old Emperor  Hirohito, who surrendered his country at the end of World War II, but went on to preside  over its economic rise.
Several Asian countries were decidedly cool however, noting the  suffering of their people at the hands of the Japanese army during the war.
The Korean  president referred to Japan and Korea's unhappy past.
Taiwan newspapers remarked that  Chinese people suffered the most from Japan's invasion.
President Reagan referred to his  reign as spanning a tumultuous and yet constructive era.
The Philippine foreign secretary  praised Hirohito as a stabilizing factor in post-war Japan. 
